UIS to break ground on student union on Wednesday
Comment
By The Associated Press
The State Journal-Register
By The Associated Press
Posted May. 3, 2016 at 6:48 AM
By The Associated Press
Posted May. 3, 2016 at 6:48 AM
The University of Illinois Springfield is preparing to break ground on its first-ever student union building.The ground-breaking for the $21.7 million project will be Wednesday morning. University of Illinois President Timothy Killeen, UIS Chancellor Susan Koch and the mayor of Springfield are scheduled to attend.The building will have two stories and 50,000 square feet. It will house campus dining, a coffee shop and an event ballroom. It also will have offices and workspaces for student government, volunteers and student organizations. It's scheduled to open in January 2018.So far the school has raised $5.3 million for the project. The
goal is $8 million before the facility opens. Campus funds and student fees will pay for the remaining $13.7 million.
By The Associated Press
